Three groups

Adopter = anybody who acquired hearing aids in Study 1 or Study 2
NonAdopter = one or both ears with â¥35 dB HL at 2kHz, but did not acquire hearing aids at any point
GoodAudio = no hearing aid acquisition, and not a candidate by the above criterion

(In graphs: Miss = 79 participants without audiograms)

Multinomial logistic regression

back to top

The reference group was NonAdopters (hearing aid candidates who did not acquire HA at any point).

Notes: 381 complete cases only (no missing data imputation), and no variable selection procedure yet.

Results:
A model with these 18 variables explains 47% of the variance, when predicting who falls into the three groups. 80% of cases are correctly classified.
Compared to NonAdopters, Adopters reported better speech understanding in noise.
Compared to NonAdopters, the âGood Audiogramâ group had better BPTA4 and less asymmetry, were less likely to live alone, but were more likely to report being lonely.

Logistic regression (Hamalainen et al.Â variables)

back to top

Comparing only Adopters and NonAdopters, 18 variables explain at most 15% of the variance in a model that predicts who adopts hearing aids. The top three variables are: the 15i-SSQ speech subscale, living alone, and social support.

Notes: List of variables resembles Hamalainen et al.Â (2021). 152 complete cases only, of a total of 171 Adopters and NonAdopters. No missing data imputation.

Comparing only Adopters and NonAdopters, 24 variables explain at 23% of the variance in a model that predicts who adopts hearing aids. The top 6 variables are: the three 15i-SSQ subscales, HHIE-S emotional subscale, WHO-BREF money question, and social support.
